---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import { site } from "../site.config";
import { b } from "../lib/baseUrl";
import { breadcrumb } from "../lib/breadcrumb";

/**
 * About page — who built this, why, and the philosophy behind it.
 *
 * SEO purpose: trust signal for AdSense + Google E-E-A-T (Experience,
 * Expertise, Authoritativeness, Trustworthiness). Reviewers and Google's
 * quality raters both check for a real human/team behind the product.
 */

const aboutSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "AboutPage",
  "@id": `${site.url}/about#about`,
  url: `${site.url}/about`,
  name: `About ${site.shortName}`,
  description: `Who built ${site.shortName} and why — the philosophy of fully client-side HEIC conversion that doesn't upload your photos.`,
  publisher: { "@id": `${site.url}/#organization` },
};

const breadcrumbLd = breadcrumb({ name: "About", path: "/about" });
---

<Layout
  title={`About — why we built a HEIC converter that never uploads`}
  description={`${site.shortName} is a fully client-side HEIC converter built on the principle that your photos should never touch someone else's server. Built by ${site.author}, free forever, no premium tier.`}
  jsonLd={[aboutSchema, breadcrumbLd]}
>
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 py-12 sm:py-16">
    <header class="mb-10">
      <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-muted)] mb-2">
        <a href={b("/")} class="hover:text-[var(--color-fg)]">{site.name}</a>
        <span class="mx-1">/</span>
        <span>About</span>
      </p>
      <h1 class="text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold tracking-tight mb-4">
        About {site.name}
      </h1>
      <p class="text-lg text-[var(--color-muted)]">
        A HEIC converter that respects your photos. Built by one developer
        in India because every other free converter on the internet
        uploads your files.
      </p>
    </header>

    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">
        The problem we couldn't stop thinking about
      </h2>
      <div class="text-[var(--color-muted)] leading-relaxed space-y-3">
        <p>
          iPhones save photos as HEIC. Most other devices — Windows PCs,
          older Androids, web tools, email clients, social platforms — don't
          know what to do with them. So millions of people search "heic to
          jpg" every month, click the first result, and upload private
          photos to someone else's server.
        </p>
        <p>
          The free tools are the worst offenders. iloveimg caps you at 5
          files unless you pay. CloudConvert caps you at 25/day. Both
          require uploading your photos to a server you can't audit.
          online-convert is plastered with ads and pop-ups. heictojpg.com
          uploads to S3 and you have no idea how long they keep it.
        </p>
        <p>
          For a routine task — open a photo your phone took — the privacy
          tradeoff is absurd. Your wedding photos shouldn't have to leave
          your device just so your aunt's Windows laptop can open them.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">
        What we built instead
      </h2>
      <div class="text-[var(--color-muted)] leading-relaxed space-y-3">
        <p>
          {site.name} runs entirely inside your browser. When you drop a
          HEIC file, it stays on your device. Conversion happens via
          WebAssembly (a compiled version of
          <a
            href="https://github.com/strukturag/libheif"
            class="text-[var(--color-accent)] hover:underline"
            rel="noopener">libheif</a
          >, the same library macOS uses internally). The output JPG, PNG,
          WebP, or AVIF is generated in your tab and offered as a download
          link or saved to a folder you pick.
        </p>
        <p>
          There is no server. There's nothing to upload to. The site is a
          bunch of static HTML, CSS, and JavaScript files on Cloudflare
          Pages — no database, no user accounts, no upload endpoint, no
          background workers processing your photos. You can disable your
          internet after the page loads and conversion still works.
        </p>
        <p>
          That architectural choice cascades into every other property of
          the product: unlimited batches (no per-conversion server cost),
          no signup (no user data to manage), no ads (no business model
          that depends on inventory), and — most importantly — no
          "free trial that becomes a subscription" because there's nothing
          to charge for.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">
        Our principles
      </h2>
      <div class="text-[var(--color-muted)] leading-relaxed space-y-4">
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-[var(--color-fg)] mb-1">
            Nothing uploads.
          </h3>
          <p>
            Every feature in {site.name} runs in your browser. We can't
            see your photos because we have no way to receive them. Open
            DevTools → Network and verify before you trust us.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-[var(--color-fg)] mb-1">
            Free forever, not "free for now."
          </h3>
          <p>
            There is no premium tier, no LTD pricing, no email-capture
            wall planned. The running cost of {site.name} is a domain
            renewal (~₹500/yr) plus Cloudflare's free Pages plan.
            See <a href={b("/free-forever")} class="text-[var(--color-accent)] hover:underline">our free-forever pledge</a> for the full breakdown.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-[var(--color-fg)] mb-1">
            Unlimited means unlimited.
          </h3>
          <p>
            Drop 5 files, 500 files, or 5000 files — the converter runs on
            your CPU. We don't impose batch caps because we don't pay for
            the conversion.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-[var(--color-fg)] mb-1">
            One tool, done well.
          </h3>
          <p>
            {site.name} converts HEIC and lets you inspect HEIC metadata.
            That's the whole product. We're not bolting on a video editor
            or a stock-photo library.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">
        Who built this
      </h2>
      <div class="text-[var(--color-muted)] leading-relaxed space-y-3">
        <p>
          {site.name} is built and maintained by {site.author}, a software
          engineer based in {site.jurisdiction}. It's part of the
          <a href={site.org.url} class="text-[var(--color-accent)] hover:underline" rel="noopener">
            {site.org.name}
          </a> family of privacy-first browser tools — small, focused
          apps that run on your device instead of the cloud.
        </p>
        <p>
          The full source isn't open at the moment (the repo is private
          while we iterate fast), but the architectural decisions, the
          stack, and the tradeoffs are all documented in <a
            href={b("/how-it-works")}
            class="text-[var(--color-accent)] hover:underline">how-it-works</a
          > and <a href={b("/free-forever")} class="text-[var(--color-accent)] hover:underline">free-forever</a>.
          If you'd like the source opened or want to contribute, get in
          touch — we'll consider it.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">
        How we keep this free
      </h2>
      <div class="text-[var(--color-muted)] leading-relaxed space-y-3">
        <p>
          The honest answer: it costs almost nothing to run. There is no
          server doing conversions on our behalf — your browser does that
          work, on your CPU, with electricity you're already paying for.
          Cloudflare Pages hosts the static files on a free plan. The
          only recurring cost is the domain (~₹500/yr).
        </p>
        <p>
          We're not running a charity — but we're also not running a
          startup that has to pay back investors. {site.name} is a side
          project that happens to be useful. Maybe one day there will be
          unobtrusive sponsorship or affiliate links to recommended
          camera gear. There will never be ads, watermarks, file caps,
          email walls, or "upgrade to remove this" friction.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">
        Get in touch
      </h2>
      <p class="text-[var(--color-muted)] leading-relaxed">
        Bug reports, feature ideas, partnership inquiries, security
        disclosures, or just to say hello —
        <a href={b("/contact")} class="text-[var(--color-accent)] hover:underline">
          here's how to reach us</a
        >.
      </p>
    </section>

    <div
      class="mt-16 rounded-xl border border-[var(--color-accent)]/40 bg-[var(--color-accent)]/[0.06] p-6 sm:p-8 text-center"
    >
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight mb-2">
        Try it now
      </h2>
      <p class="text-[var(--color-muted)] mb-4">
        Drop a HEIC file. See for yourself that it never leaves your device.
      </p>
      <a
        href={b("/")}
        class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-5 py-2.5 rounded-md bg-[var(--color-accent)] text-[var(--color-accent-fg)] font-semibold hover:bg-[var(--color-accent-hover)] transition-colors no-underline"
      >
        Open the converter
        <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" class="w-4 h-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true">
          <path d="M5 12h14M13 5l7 7-7 7"/>
        </svg>
      </a>
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>
